Great explanation from the video — now I’ll compress + sharpen it so you can actually use Flyweight in interviews and real design without confusion.

🧠 1️⃣ Flyweight Pattern — One Line
Reduce memory by sharing common data across multiple objects
🎯 Core Idea

👉 Don’t duplicate heavy data again and again

Visual Intuition
4
🔥 The Problem (Why Flyweight Exists)
❌ Without Flyweight
10 lakh objects × 30KB each = HUGE memory (GBs)

👉 Every object stores:

type

image (sprite)

position

💣 Reality
Most data is SAME across objects

Example:

All humanoid robots → same image + same type
Only position differs
🧠 KEY CONCEPT (MOST IMPORTANT)
🟢 Intrinsic vs Extrinsic
🔹 Intrinsic (Shared)
✔ Same across objects
✔ Stored inside object
✔ Cached

Examples:

robot type

sprite/image

font style (text editor)

🔸 Extrinsic (Dynamic)
✔ Changes per object
✔ Passed from outside
✔ NOT stored inside

Examples:

x, y position

row, column

color (if dynamic)

🎯 Golden Rule
Intrinsic → shared  
Extrinsic → passed
🚀 Flyweight Solution Flow
Step 1: Remove extrinsic data
class Robot {
    String type;      // intrinsic
    Sprite sprite;    // intrinsic
}
Step 2: Pass extrinsic in method
void display(int x, int y);
Step 3: Cache objects
Map<String, Robot> cache;
Step 4: Reuse objects
if(cache.contains(type)) return existing;
else create and store;
💻 Final Flow (IMPORTANT)
Client → Factory → (cache hit?) → reuse / create → return
🎮 Gaming Example (Simplified)
❌ Before
new Robot(x, y, "humanoid", sprite); // repeated 5 lakh times
✅ After Flyweight
Robot robot = factory.get("humanoid");
robot.display(x, y);
💥 Result
Objects created: 10 lakh → 2 only
Memory saved: HUGE
📝 Text Editor Example (INTERVIEW FAVORITE)
Problem
"This is text..."

👉 1000 'T' characters → 1000 objects ❌

Solution
1 object for 'T'
Reuse everywhere
Code Idea
Letter l = factory.get('T');
l.display(row, col);
🧠 Pattern Recognition (VERY IMPORTANT)
When interviewer says:
✔ Memory constraint
✔ Millions of similar objects
✔ Repeated heavy data
✔ Game / editor / rendering

👉 Immediately think:

FLYWEIGHT
🔥 Real-Life Use Cases
🎮 Games
Trees, bullets, enemies, particles
📝 Text Editors
Characters, fonts
🌍 Maps
Icons, markers
🧱 UI Rendering
Buttons, components
⚠️ When NOT to Use
❌ Objects are unique (no shared data)
❌ Low object count
❌ Complexity not worth it
🧠 Advantages
✔ Huge memory optimization
✔ Faster performance (less creation)
✔ Reusability
⚠️ Trade-offs
❌ More complex code
❌ Requires careful design
❌ Hard debugging sometimes
🔥 Comparison (VERY IMPORTANT)
Flyweight vs Singleton
Singleton → 1 object globally  
Flyweight → many shared objects (per type)
Flyweight vs Object Pool
Flyweight → share intrinsic data  
Object Pool → reuse full objects
🎯 Interview Answer (Perfect)
Definition
Flyweight is a structural design pattern that reduces memory usage by sharing common intrinsic data among multiple objects while externalizing varying data.
Example (Quick)
Game with 10 lakh robots → share sprite → pass position
🧠 Final Mental Model
Too many similar objects → Flyweight
🔥 Super Simple Memory Trick
Don’t store duplicate data → share it